        "timestamp": "2019-02-07 13:56:24.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1\n\n(1 comment)\n\nAs the primary point is to increase test coverage, this should do it, though additional tests could be performed.",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "e058d52541bdb484ba9929816fddd92fc0615240",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 3813,
          "name": "Lathishbabu Ganesan",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "lathishbabu.ganesan@est.tech",
          "username": "Lathish"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-02-07 15:27:48.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nThe context is a mocked object so I doubt there is no way to assert it that's why I have used verify.",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "0375aeffa99dc92d6a867ebb6daae038cac862b5",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-02-07 15:46:25.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> The context is a mocked object so I doubt there is no way to assert\n > it that's why I have used verify.\n\nBecause ctx is a mock, you could always verify that one or more of its methods was invoked, as a side-effect of the start()/stop() calls.  For instance, if you expect the start() method to invoke getBundle, then: verify(ctx).getBundle()",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "da4982ade50a805c3e301106f3a12de3fe8bf339",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-02-07 15:47:40.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nThere may be other things you can check, too.  For instance, once start() completes, is there anything that's running?  Is there an \"alive\" flag you can check?  Similar thoughts for stop().",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "bf0bc7b6e32ac96e85e7588097a9304fb8cb6439",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 3813,
          "name": "Lathishbabu Ganesan",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "lathishbabu.ganesan@est.tech",
          "username": "Lathish"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-02-07 16:17:25.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nThis is the start method with mocked context object.\n\n    @Override\n    public void start(BundleContext ctx) throws Exception {\n\n        SourceSystemNode sourceSystemNode = new SourceSystemNode();\n        log.info(\"Registering service \" + sourceSystemNode.getClass().getName());\n        registrations.add(ctx.registerService(sourceSystemNode.getClass().getName(), sourceSystemNode, null));\n        log.info(\"Registering service sccessful for  \" + sourceSystemNode.getClass().getName());\n    }",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "1d1b801a6099daac3c9c433711fd97db86711269",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-02-07 16:28:17.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> This is the start method with mocked context object.\n > \n > @Override\n > public void start(BundleContext ctx) throws Exception {\n > \n > SourceSystemNode sourceSystemNode = new SourceSystemNode();\n > log.info(\"Registering service \" + sourceSystemNode.getClass().getName());\n > registrations.add(ctx.registerService(sourceSystemNode.getClass().getName(),\n > sourceSystemNode, null));\n > log.info(\"Registering service sccessful for  \" + sourceSystemNode.getClass().getName());\n > }\n\nSo you can verify that ctx.registerService() gets invoked.  Or, even better, you could use powermock to verify that that the activator's registration list now has another entry based on what was returned by ctx.registerService().",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "8107a789ec57abb9c116ff9f6680de5debeb1489",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 3813,
          "name": "Lathishbabu Ganesan",
